{"identifier":{"url":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language\/AboutTheLanguageReference","interfaceLanguage":"swift"},"abstract":[{"text":"Read the notation that the formal grammar uses.","type":"text"}],"schemaVersion":{"minor":3,"patch":0,"major":0},"primaryContentSections":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This part of the book describes the formal grammar of the Swift programming language."},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"The grammar described here is intended to help you understand the language in more"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"detail, rather than to allow you to directly implement a parser or compiler.","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"The Swift language is relatively small, because many common types, functions, and operators","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"that appear virtually everywhere in Swift code","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"are actually defined in the Swift standard library. Although these types, functions,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and operators aren’t part of the Swift language itself,"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"they’re used extensively in the discussions and code examples in this part of the book.","type":"text"}]},{"anchor":"How-to-Read-the-Grammar","type":"heading","text":"How to Read the Grammar","level":2},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"The notation used to describe the formal grammar of the Swift programming language"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"follows a few conventions:","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"},{"type":"unorderedList","items":[{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"An arrow (→) is used to mark grammar productions and can be read as “can consist of.”","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Syntactic categories are indicated by ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"italic","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" text and appear on both sides","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"of a grammar production rule."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"text":"Literal words and punctuation are indicated by ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"boldface constant width","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"strong"},{"type":"text","text":" text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"and appear only on the right-hand side of a grammar production rule."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Alternative grammar productions are separated by vertical"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"bars (|). When alternative productions are too long to read easily,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"they’re broken into multiple grammar production rules on new lines."}],"type":"paragraph"}]},{"content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"In a few cases, regular font text is used to describe the right-hand side"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"of a grammar production rule.","type":"text"}]}]},{"content":[{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"Optional syntactic categories and literals are marked by a trailing"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"question mark, ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}]},{"text":".","type":"text"}],"type":"paragraph"}]}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"As an example, the grammar of a getter-setter block is defined as follows:","type":"text"}]},{"type":"aside","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-setter-block"}]},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"?","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"}"}]},{"type":"text","text":" | "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"{","type":"codeVoice"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}]}]}],"name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block","style":"note"},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"This definition indicates that a getter-setter block can consist of a getter clause"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"text":"followed by an optional setter clause, enclosed in braces,","type":"text"},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"or","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" a setter clause followed by a getter clause, enclosed in braces."},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"text":"The grammar production above is equivalent to the following two productions,","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"text","text":"where the alternatives are spelled out explicitly:"}]},{"style":"note","type":"aside","name":"Grammar of a getter-setter block","content":[{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"text":"","type":"text"}]},{"type":"paragraph","inlineContent":[{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-setter-block","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-clause","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"setter-clause"}]},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"?"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"text","text":"\n"},{"inlineContent":[{"text":"getter-setter-block","type":"text"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" → "},{"type":"strong","inlineContent":[{"type":"codeVoice","code":"{"}]},{"text":" ","type":"text"},{"type":"emphasis","inlineContent":[{"text":"setter-clause","type":"text"}]},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"type":"text","text":"getter-clause"}],"type":"emphasis"},{"type":"text","text":" "},{"inlineContent":[{"code":"}","type":"codeVoice"}],"type":"strong"}]}]}],"kind":"content"}],"metadata":{"title":"About the Language Reference"},"kind":"article","sections":[],"hierarchy":{"paths":[["doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language"]]},"references":{"doc://org.swift.tspl/documentation/The-Swift-Programming-Language":{"url":"\/documentation\/the-swift-programming-language","identifier":"doc:\/\/org.swift.tspl\/documentation\/The-Swift-Programming-Language","kind":"article","role":"collection","abstract":[],"type":"topic","title":"The Swift Programming Language (5.9.2)"}}}